 and the figure of the merchant during a period of economic liberalization in the 2000s. Rather than seeing these social structures and representations as expressions of a timeless bazaar culture, or as shaped only by Islamic tradition, Exchange Ideologies relates them to processes of politically managed economic liberalization and the Syrian regime's attempts to ensure its own survival in the midst of change. In doing so, Anderson provides an account of economic liberalization in Syria as a social and cultural process as much as a political and economic one.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aAnthropology. 4aMiddle East Studies. 4aUrban Studies. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Syria.2bisacsh  aeconomic liberalisation in Syria, merchant-state relations in Syria, trader's in Aleppo's Bazaar, authoritarian rule of Bashar al-Asad, Syria’s civil war.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176828640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501768286423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501768286/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK